{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b04764a8-65a1-4d35-9444-94406783fa92","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK went up → workload versions need to go up too → `dotnet workload update`.\n\nIf issues persist after updating, you can also try:\n```bash\ndotnet workload update --from-previous-sdk\n```\nThis carries forward workloads that were installed for your previous SDK version.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"55a1e5c2-7b12-4085-9215-e3559d123581","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search the codebase for this.","outputTokens":258,"requestId":"7FD9:39A45D:613CC1A:6A02BF2:69F15637"},"id":"e5c25333-48db-490d-a66d-ac352ccc658b","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:52:15.703Z","parentId":"cd37ec51-3697-488c-a7e4-ed1b6e9764db"}
